Jackson Heights has no shortage of great food, and this branch of the Homemade Taqueria is no exception.

The simple dining room is very relaxed, almost cafeteria-style. The menu is broken down by category: tacos, tortas, encheladas, nachos, quessadillas, tostadas, burritos, huaraches, and picaditas.

Given that the tortillas are homemade (hence the name), we ordered a couple of tacos, an order of huaraches, and some guacamole. As expected, the tortillas and, therefore, the chips were excellent.

They also offer fresh juice, so I ordered a lemonade and watched them squeeze fresh lime into the blender, which was terrific.

The food arrived with three sauces: a roasted tomatillo salsa, a ‚Äúguacamole‚Äù style sauce, and a spice chile sauce. All were hard to stop eating. Of the two tacos we ordered, the Beria was much better. The chicken taco was a little bland, but that‚Äôs what the salsa was for. The Huaraches were tasty; I ordered them with Al Pastor, which came with lots of pineapple mixed in.

Many people ordered quesadillas, which looked fantastic as well.

If you are in the area, it‚Äôs a fun spot to pop in and have a quick bite. You can even sit on the stools by the window and watch the tortillas being made outside. It‚Äôs funny that they are made (literally) outside of both the kitchen and the restaurant, but who cares? They were great.
